title: "The Shape of Discovery: Detecting Topological Precursors to Technological Breakthroughs in the USPTO Patent Citation Network"
abstract: >-
  Applies persistent homology to the U.S. patent citation network (~8M patents,
  ~118M citations, 1976-2023) to test whether topological signatures precede
  technological breakthroughs. The central finding is null: an apparent
  precursor signal (Wilcoxon p < 0.001) is entirely explained by a temporal
  confound — beta-1 declines ~1.8/year across all 28 CPC pairs due to network
  maturation, and z-scores correlate with filing year (Spearman rho = -0.921).
  After per-pair linear detrending, the signal vanishes (Wilcoxon p = 0.85).
  N=65 curated breakthroughs (57 valid comparisons), seven confound robustness
  checks. The project demonstrates that temporal trends in TDA on evolving
  networks produce spurious signals — a methodological cautionary tale.
  Conceptual design, analytical framework, and implementation by Claude
  (Anthropic). Facilitated by Christopher Ortiz.
version: v3.0.0
